{"title":"Lifting Layers: Analysis and Applications","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Common activations like ReLU discard negative responses and create zero-gradient regions, and simple one-hidden-layer regressors with ReLUs lead to non-convex training; in contrast, low-dimensional regression often relies on linear splines.","method":"Introduce a lifting layer that maps a scalar x to a higher-dimensional vector using ordered labels t1<...<tL (barycentric-like encoding). In its simplest form it behaves like two complementary ReLUs, avoiding zero-gradient plateaus. When followed by a fully connected linear layer, the network represents a continuous piecewise-linear (linear spline) function (Proposition 2) that can approximate any continuous function arbitrarily well (Corollary 3). With a convex loss, learning reduces to a convex optimization over linear parameters (Proposition 5). The construction extends to multidimensional inputs via vector-valued lifting on a triangulation or coordinate-wise lifting for high dimensions (Section 3.3)."},{"problem":"Robust training with non-convex or flat losses (e.g., truncated linear) is difficult and prone to local minima in standard networks.","method":"Lift the network’s output (and the input to the loss) into a higher-dimensional space tailored to the loss; predict within the convex hull of the lifted range and map back via the inverse lifting. This converts minimization of a non-convex loss into a convex problem in the loss-layer parameters (Proposition 9), yielding a linear objective with simplex constraints and even a closed-form solution via per-column argmin over a cost matrix. The approach robustly fits data with heavy outliers, as demonstrated on a regression task with 40% outliers using a truncated linear loss (Example 10)."}]}
